Current limits and follow-up actions
• Current validated concurrency is 45 peak VUs across auth, catalog, circulation, and ingestion workflows for two minutes on the seeded dataset used in testing.
• The same k6 suite should be re-run after large-scale data population milestones such as 10k+ or 100k-book datasets.
• Catalog filtering still includes some in-memory filtering patterns for remaining fields such as year/language and should be pushed fully into SQL in a future pass.
• Readiness checks currently hit the database on every request and may need rate limiting or short caching under heavier probe frequency.
• Ingestion should continue to be monitored at p95 and p99 because it is the slowest end-to-end flow.


7. Bulk Upload Readiness Notes
The current bulk-upload documentation describes support for both CSV and JSON catalog imports, with Papa Parse used for client-side CSV parsing and transformation into the backend book-ingestion payload structure. This is suitable for operator-driven imports, but it is not yet a final large-scale ingestion architecture.
Current approach
Current limitations
Supports .csv and .json uploads; CSV is parsed client-side, transformed to backend shape, and submitted to /api/ingest/books. UI uses drag-and-drop and clear upload feedback.
Very large files may stress browser memory; the current single-payload model can hit request-size limits; row-level partial failure reporting is limited; header mapping is rigid and expects specific column names.

