9. Rollback Plan
A formal rollback path is required even when launch is presentation-oriented. The objective is to restore the last known-good state quickly if a deployment introduces authentication regressions, broken core workflows, or environment-key misconfiguration.
Rollback trigger conditions
• Authentication or session failures block access to the dashboard.
• Catalog, circulation, or ingestion flows fail during smoke tests.
• Unexpected 5xx errors appear immediately after deployment.
• Critical environment variables are missing or mis-scoped.
• Performance degradation is severe enough to block demonstration use.
Rollback procedure
• Pause further testing and record the exact failing step, timestamp, and deployment version.
• Re-deploy the last known-good frontend and backend artifacts.
• Revert or re-apply the last stable database migration state only if the release introduced a schema-dependent failure and the rollback plan has been reviewed.
• Re-run the smoke checklist on the restored version.
• Document the root cause and block re-release until the issue is corrected and revalidated.
